, name: 'Event 2', duration: 60 },\n  ];\n  const result = schedule(events, rooms, defaultOptions);\n  expect(result.assignments).toHaveLength(2);\n  // With 2 rooms available and no prerequisites, events should be placed\n  // in different rooms at the same start time\n  expect(result.assignments[0].roomId).not.toBe(result.assignments[1].roomId);\n  expect(result.assignments[0].startTime).toBe(result.assignments[1].startTime);\n});\n```\n\n#### 14. Missing test coverage for important edge cases\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/scheduler.test.ts`\n\nThe following scenarios are not tested:\n- **Empty rooms array with non-empty events** -- should all events be unscheduled?\n- **Events where backtracking actually outperforms greedy** -- the tests never verify that the backtracking path produces a better result than greedy alone. There is no test where greedy fails to schedule N events but backtracking succeeds with N+1.\n- **Duplicate event IDs** -- undefined behavior currently.\n- **Negative gap / negative duration** -- undefined behavior.\n- **Large number of prerequisites forming a deep chain** -- testing topological sort at scale.\n- **Event with a prerequisite that itself cannot be scheduled** -- e.g., prerequisite fails capacity check, so dependent must also fail.\n\n#### 15. The comment on line 149 says \"Greedy approach with smart room selection\" but the function docstring on line 125 says \"backtracking to maximize\"\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/scheduler.ts`, lines 125, 149\n\nThe `schedule` function's docstring says it uses \"backtracking to maximize the number of scheduled events,\" but the main body is a greedy algorithm. Backtracking is only invoked as a fallback when greedy does not schedule everything. The docstring should reflect this two-phase approach.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | Issue | Location |\n|---|----------|-------|----------|\n| 1 | Critical | Dangling prerequisite handling is accidental, not intentional | `scheduler.ts:26-39` |\n| 2 | Critical | Gap-checking loop has confusing dead-code branch and subtle correctness risk | `scheduler.ts:99-113` |\n| 3 | Critical | Gap semantics ambiguity (same-room vs prerequisite gap) | `scheduler.ts:82` |\n| 4 | Critical | Gap enforcement correctness relies on fragile condition interactions | `scheduler.ts:99-113` |\n| 5 | Important | Backtracking does not explore different start time orderings | `scheduler.ts:260-337` |\n| 6 | Important | Large-input strategies don't respect topological order natively | `scheduler.ts:363-396` |\n| 7 | Important | Early return skips secondary optimization when all events fit | `scheduler.ts:213-219` |\n| 8 | Important | Duplicate event IDs not validated | `scheduler.ts:136-139` |\n| 9 | Important | No validation for negative/nonsensical inputs | `scheduler.ts`, `types.ts` |\n| 10 | Suggestion | Repeated room sorting and linear lookups | `scheduler.ts:142,165,257` |\n| 11 | Suggestion | Room assignments re-sorted on every findEarliestStart call | `scheduler.ts:94` |\n| 12 | Suggestion | Unused `_rooms` parameter | `scheduler.ts:363` |\n| 13 | Suggestion | Empty assertion in concurrent-room test | `scheduler.test.ts:197-212` |\n| 14 | Suggestion | Missing test coverage for important edge cases | `scheduler.test.ts` |\n| 15 | Suggestion | Misleading function docstring | `scheduler.ts:125` |\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- **Type definitions** in `/workspace/src/types.ts` are clean, well-structured, and exactly match the specification.\n- **Cycle detection** via three-color DFS is a textbook correct implementation for directed graphs. Self-reference cycles, direct cycles, and indirect cycles are all correctly caught and tested.\n- **The two-phase approach** (greedy then backtracking fallback) is a pragmatic design that handles most cases efficiently while providing optimization for harder scenarios.\n- **The pruning optimization** on line 282 (`remaining + current <= best`) is a correct and effective branch-and-bound cut